description.plain:
Carissa’s Wierd formed in 1995 in Seattle after Matt Brooke and Jenn Ghetto (later Jenn Champion) moved from Tuscon to Seattle and added pianist Jeff Hellis and a revolving door of percussionists and violinists.

Ugly But Honest: 1996-1999 was the group’s first official release in 2000. After the addition of Ben Bridwell on drums (then bass later), You Should Be At Home Here followed in 2001. That same year, a single “You Should Be Hated Here”, backed with a cover of Morrissey’s “Suedehead”, was released by Sub Pop as part of the second run of the label’s Singles Club. Their next album Songs About Leaving was released on Sad Robot Records the following year.

After releasing a collection of rare and unreleased songs as Wierd Scrap Book, the group disbanded in November 2003. Live tracks from the band’s farewell show, along with studio recordings of three previously unrecorded songs, came out posthumously in 2004 as I Before E.

Ghetto formed S in 2001 while in Carissa’s Wierd as a solo project, and has continued releasing music under that name. Brooke and Bridwell went on to form Band Of Horses, but Brooke left soon after the band released their debut album in 2006.

Another posthumous Carissa’s Wierd collection titled They’ll Only Miss You When You Leave: Songs 1996-2003 surfaced in 2010, and a 7" single featuring two more songs appeared in 2011.

description.plain:
This song juxtaposes “leaving” as in leaving a partner with “leaving” as in dying.

In the first part of the song a character is broken up with, or is the one doing the breaking up. Either way, it’s messy on them, and some of the lines clearly hint at a breakup.

It seems the narrator had some depression before the loss of their significant other and the loss drives him to the edge which leads into the next part of the song, which seems to very cryptically describe a suicide.
